'''''Conflict 2500''''' is video game published by [[Avalon Hill]] in 1981 for the [[Apple II series|Apple II]], [[Atari 8-bit computers]], [[Commodore PET]], and [[TRS-80]].<ref name=manual/>

==Gameplay==
''Conflict 2500'' is a game in which the player must use a band of warships to seek and destroy invading berserkers moving invisibly.<ref name="SG"/>

==Development==
The game was designed by William David Volk.<ref name=manual/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/author/william-volk |title=William Volk &#124; HuffPost |publisher=Huffingtonpost.com |access-date=2018-05-31}}</ref><ref name="Conflict 2500">{{cite web|title=Conflict 2500|url=http://www.elisoftware.org/index.php?title=Conflict_2500_(Apple_II,_5_1/4%22_Disk)_Avalon_Hill_-_1981_USA,_Canada_Release|website=Elis' Software Encyclopedia|access-date=5 December 2014}}</ref> Volk says that at the time he was a fan of the animated series ''[[Star Blazers]]'' and borrowed themes from the show for ''Conflict 2500''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/104515/Playing_Catch_Up_Conflict_2500s_William_Volk.php |title=Playing Catch Up: Conflict 2500's William Volk |publisher=Gamasutra |date=2007-04-19 |access-date=2018-05-31}}</ref> Volk also explained that he had played the ''Startrek'' game and wanted a more complex version of that game.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://obsoletegamer.com/the-interview-william-d-volk/ |title=The Interview: William D. Volk |date=7 October 2010 |publisher=Obsoletegamer.com |access-date=2018-05-31}}</ref>

==Reception==
Jon Mishcon reviewed ''Conflict 2500'' in ''[[The Space Gamer]]'' No. 45.<ref name="SG">{{cite journal|last= Mishcon |first= Jon  |date=November 1981 |title=Capsule Reviews|journal=[[The Space Gamer]]|publisher=[[Steve Jackson Games]]|issue=45|page=33}}</ref> Mishcon commented that "Not great, but easily worth [the price]."<ref name="SG"/>

